<BaseLayout title="Donor-Filter Hypothesis" description="The IMWA's emerging theory that MinistryWatch's persistent popup is not a design failure but a design feature — a mechanism for identifying and retaining donors by filtering out non-donors. The Institute neither endorses nor refutes this. The Institute watches it.">
  <article class="page">
    <div class="doc-header">
      <div class="doc-classification">IMWA WORKING HYPOTHESIS · DFH-2026-001 · NOT YET PEER REVIEWED</div>
      <h1>The Donor-Filter Hypothesis</h1>
      <div class="doc-subtitle">An Emerging Theory Regarding the Strategic Function of the MinistryWatch.com Solicitation Apparatus</div>
      <div class="doc-meta">
        <span>Status: <strong>Hypothesis — Under Observation</strong></span>
        <span>Originated: Solicitation Watch, Part I (June 27, 2026)</span>
        <span>Endorsed by the Institute: No</span>
        <span>Refuted by the Institute: Also no</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Statement of the Hypothesis</h2>
      <p>The Donor-Filter Hypothesis holds that <strong>the MinistryWatch.com solicitation popup is not a design failure but a design feature.</strong></p>
      <p>More specifically: the hypothesis proposes that the popup's persistence across visits — its refusal to remember prior dismissal, its reappearance regardless of the visitor's expressed preference — is not the result of oversight or technical limitation, but of intentional strategic design aimed at filtering the MinistryWatch visitor population toward those most likely to donate.</p>
      <p>The Institute neither endorses nor refutes this hypothesis. The Institute watches it. This page documents the hypothesis, the reasoning behind it, its supporting evidence, its weaknesses, and the Institute's current observational posture. We consider this documentation a public service.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Argument</h2>
      <p>The hypothesis proceeds in four steps:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Audience Characterization:</strong> MinistryWatch's audience consists, by definition, of people who care about Christian ministry accountability. This population skews, the Institute hypothesizes, toward charitable disposition — individuals who have thought carefully about giving and who are, in aggregate, more likely than the general population to respond positively to donation requests.</li>
        <li><strong>Filter Mechanism:</strong> A popup that aggressively solicits donations upon every visit, that cannot be permanently dismissed, and that treats every returning visitor as a stranger will, over time, drive away visitors who are unwilling to be persistently solicited. These visitors will not return, or will return rarely.</li>
        <li><strong>Population Selection:</strong> The visitors who continue returning despite the popup are, by revealed preference, those who tolerate — or welcome — being asked for money on a recurring basis. This population is, by definition, more likely to eventually donate than the population that left.</li>
        <li><strong>Strategic Conclusion:</strong> The popup is therefore a donor-identification and population-selection mechanism. MinistryWatch is not failing to remember that a visitor has dismissed the popup. MinistryWatch is testing whether the visitor is the kind of person who gives.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Evidence For</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The popup's persistence is technically trivial to fix. A single cookie or localStorage entry would suppress it for returning visitors. MinistryWatch has not done this. Intentionality is one explanation for a trivially fixable problem that has not been fixed.</li>
        <li>MinistryWatch's mission explicitly centers on donor wisdom. An organization thinking carefully about donors might also think carefully about which donors it attracts.</li>
        <li>The popup's copy — "If MinistryWatch has helped you give wisely, would you consider making a gift?" — addresses a visitor who has already given wisely at least once, suggesting a mental model of a recurring, committed audience rather than a first-time visitor.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Evidence Against</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The IMWA's VIGIL-1 Algorithmic Counsel, upon reviewing the hypothesis, noted that "the simplest explanation for a popup that doesn't remember its dismissals is a popup that doesn't remember its dismissals." VIGIL-1 declined to elaborate. The Institute found this response insufficient but was unable to counter it formally.</li>
        <li>The popup was ultimately removed on July 1, 2026 — after the Institute's Solicitation Watch series had documented it across five installments. If the popup were a deliberate strategic instrument, one would expect a more deliberate withdrawal. The Institute observed no evidence of deliberation.</li>
        <li>The Institute cannot rule out the mundane explanation, which is that nobody set a persistent cookie and nobody noticed until they did. The Institute finds this explanation less interesting than the hypothesis and has accordingly deprioritized it, though it remains in the file.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Current Status</h2>
      <p>The Donor-Filter Hypothesis is active. It has not been confirmed. It has not been refuted. The popup's removal on July 1 introduced new data that is consistent with both the hypothesis (the filter was deliberately retired at fiscal year end) and the mundane explanation (someone turned it off when they came into the office).</p>
      <p>The Institute will continue to watch MinistryWatch's solicitation behavior in the new fiscal year. If the new fiscal year produces a new popup with similar characteristics, the hypothesis gains significant support. If the new fiscal year produces a popup with persistent dismissal memory, the hypothesis may be retired. If the new fiscal year produces no popup at all, the Institute will note this as unprecedented and open a new inquiry.</p>
      <p>The Institute watches. The hypothesis watches with us.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="signature-block">
      <p>Published by the <strong>Institute for Ministry Watch Accountability</strong><br />Solicitation Watch Working Group</p>
      <p class="sig-disclaimer">The Donor-Filter Hypothesis is a working theory, not a finding. It has not been peer reviewed, because the IMWA does not have peers in this specific area of inquiry. If you believe you are a peer, please contact the Institute. We are open to this.</p>
